Executors Framework in Java

The Executors Framework was introduced in  java5 as part of the java.util.concurrent package
to simplify the development of concurrent applications by abstracting away many of the complexities
involved in creating and managing threads.

Problems before Executors Framework:

1. Manual Thread Management
2. Resource Management
3. Scalability
4. Thread Reuse
5. Error handling


Executors framework has three thinks

1. Executor -> this is a interface
2. ExecutorService -> this is service implementation using executor interface
3. ScheduledExecutorService -> as the name suggested for Scheduled....


How ThreadPool Internally works:

Architecture:

        Tasks Submitted
              |
              v
        Blocking Queue
              |
              v
     Worker Threads (Pool)
     |      |       |
     T1     T2      T3

Steps:

1. Task is submitted
2. If a thread is free → execute
3. If all threads busy → task goes to queue
4. When thread becomes free → picks task from queue


What is Future?

A Future is returned when you submit a task to an ExecutorService.
It let you:
Check if the task is done
Get the result(blocking)
Cancel the task

ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);

Future<?> future = executor.submit(() -> {
    Thread.Sleep(2000);
    return 42;
});


Runnable vs Callable

 Runnable -> no return value
 Callable<T> -> returns value -> used with Future

 Future<?> f1 = executor.submit(() -> System.out.println("Runnable"));
 Future<Integer> f2 = executor.submit(() -> 10); // Callable



Problem with Future
Cannot chain tasks
No callback mechanism
Blocking nature

👉 That’s why Java introduced:
➡️ CompletableFuture (very important for interviews)